####-----Reading in Data and Stacking it ----- ####
#Reading in files
files <- list.files('../data',full.names=T)


#Read in individual data files

ndmi <- read_csv(files[1]) %>% 
  rename(burned=2,unburned=3) %>%
  mutate(data='ndmi')


ndsi <- read_csv(files[2]) %>% 
  rename(burned=2,unburned=3) %>%
  mutate(data='ndsi')

ndvi <- read_csv(files[3])%>% 
  rename(burned=2,unburned=3) %>%
  mutate(data='ndvi')

# Stack as a tidy dataset
full_long <- rbind(ndvi,ndmi,ndsi) %>%
  gather(key='site',value='value',-DateTime,-data) %>%
  filter(!is.na(value))

What is the correlation between NDVI and NDMI? - here I want you to convert the full_long dataset in to a wide dataset using the function “spread” and then make a plot that shows the correlation s a function of if the site was burned or not (x axis should be ndmi) You should exclude winter months and focus on summer months

# Spread the dataset
full_short <- spread(full_long, data, value) %>%
  mutate(month = month(DateTime)) %>%
  filter(month %in% c(5,6,7,8,9))

#used mutate to only have growing months

#use ggplot to make a graph with ndmi on x axis
ggplot(full_short,aes(x = ndmi, y= ndvi, color = site)) +
  geom_point()+
  theme_few()+
  scale_color_colorblind()

Based on the ndmi vs ndmi analysis, it can be seen that there is a greater variability in values for the burned sites. This larger range shows that there are many sites with lower ndmi and ndvi values during the growing season after burn.

Figure 3 shows ## Q3

How is the snow effect from question 2 different between pre- and post-burn and burned and unburned? The pre-burn and unburned sites have a similar trend in ndsi and ndmi values. However, the post-burn sites have lower ndsi and ndmi values. This means that there is less vegetation present, and less persistence of snow. Ultimately, the snow decreases in areas that have been burned.
